        <!-- How It Works Section -->
        <h2>How NASDAQ Proposes It Would Work <span>Based on SEC filing SR-NASDAQ-2025-072</span></h2>
        
        <div class="step-container">
            <div class="step-header">
                <div class="step-number">01</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h3>Order Placement & Execution</h3>
                    <p>Investor places order on NASDAQ and selects settlement preference: traditional or tokenized. Both execute on the <strong>same order book</strong> with identical price-time priority. No separate liquidity pools.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="xaults-perspective">
                <div class="xaults-perspective-label">Xaults Perspective</div>
                <p>Similar to NSE/BSE unified order matching ‚Äî no fragmented liquidity. This architecture preserves market depth while adding optionality.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="step-container">
            <div class="step-header">
                <div class="step-number">02</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h3>Settlement via DTC</h3>
                    <p>Trade settles through DTC's permissioned blockchain infrastructure. <strong>Same CUSIP number</strong> for both forms ‚Äî tokenized and traditional shares are fully interchangeable at any time.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="xaults-perspective">
                <div class="xaults-perspective-label">Xaults Perspective</div>
                <p>Like ISIN remaining identical whether held in CDSL or NSDL ‚Äî the identifier stays constant, only the settlement rail differs.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="step-container">
            <div class="step-header">
                <div class="step-number">03</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h3>Token Minting & Custody</h3>
                    <p>Token minted to participant's registered wallet. All shareholder rights transfer with the token ‚Äî voting, dividends, liquidation claims remain <strong>identical to traditional shares</strong>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="xaults-perspective">
                <div class="xaults-perspective-label">Xaults Perspective</div>
                <p>Rights unchanged whether physical, demat, or tokenized form. CDSL/NSDL could theoretically add blockchain rail alongside existing systems.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Regulatory Framework Box -->
        <div class="reg-framework">
            <h3>‚öñÔ∏è Regulatory Framework: What the SEC Required</h3>
            <div class="reg-grid">
                <div class="reg-item">
                    <h4>What Framework?</h4>
                    <p>Existing SEC/NMS regulations. NASDAQ operates tokenized trading under its current exchange license ‚Äî no new regulatory category created.</p>
                    <div class="source"><a href="https://www.sec.gov/files/rules/sro/nasdaq/2025/34-103989.pdf" target="_blank">‚Üí SEC Filing ¬ß3.2</a></div>
                </div>
                <div class="reg-item">
                    <h4>Exemptions Granted?</h4>
                    <p><strong>None.</strong> NASDAQ explicitly did not request exemptions. All existing investor protections, surveillance, and reporting requirements remain in force.</p>
                    <div class="source"><a href="https://www.nasdaq.com/newsroom/qa-nasdaqs-new-proposal-tokenized-securities" target="_blank">‚Üí NASDAQ Q&A</a></div>
                </div>
                <div class="reg-item">
                    <h4>Key Conditions</h4>
                    <p>Permissioned blockchain only. DTC as central operator. T+1 settlement maintained. Full audit trail. Registered wallets only.</p>
                    <div class="source"><a href="https://www.dtcc.com/news/2025/december/11/paving-the-way-to-tokenized-dtc-custodied-assets" target="_blank">‚Üí DTCC Announcement</a></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

