        <!-- Xaults Perspective Section -->
        <div class="perspective-section">
            <div class="perspective-header">
                <h3>Xaults Perspective</h3>
                <span class="perspective-badge">Internal Analysis</span>
            </div>
            <p class="perspective-note">The following observations represent Xaults' interpretation and potential relevance to Indian capital markets.</p>
            
            <div class="perspective-grid">
                <div class="perspective-card highlight">
                    <h4>üîó Direct Alignment with Xaults Approach</h4>
                    <p>The NASDAQ filing explicitly states that tokenized securities must be "fungible with, share the same CUSIP number with, and afford shareholders the same material rights and privileges" as traditional securities. This is precisely how Xaults structures tokenized trade finance instruments ‚Äî programmable tokens backed by real banking infrastructure, maintaining full legal equivalence with traditional instruments.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="perspective-card">
                    <h4>Depository Infrastructure Parallel</h4>
                    <p>DTCC's central role mirrors potential CDSL/NSDL positioning. The U.S. approach keeps existing depositories central rather than disintermediating them ‚Äî aligning with SEBI's regulatory philosophy.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="perspective-card">
                    <h4>Settlement Cycle Positioning</h4>
                    <p>India already operates at T+1. The U.S. is tokenizing partly to reach what India has achieved through traditional rails. Different starting points, potentially similar destinations.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="perspective-card">
                    <h4>No Exemption Model</h4>
                    <p>NASDAQ's explicit decision to operate within existing securities law (no exemptions) sets a precedent. Tokenization positioned as operational upgrade, not regulatory carve-out.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="perspective-card">
                    <h4>Exchange-Led Approach</h4>
                    <p>The U.S. approach is exchange-initiated (NASDAQ filing) with regulatory approval. India could consider NSE/BSE-led proposals or a SEBI-initiated sandbox framework.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="perspective-card">
                    <h4>Sandbox Precedent</h4>
                    <p>RBI's regulatory sandbox has successfully tested tokenization concepts. A similar SEBI sandbox for securities tokenization could enable controlled exploration without systemic risk.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

